&lt;blockquote&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Thereâ€™s nothing as flashy and useful for JavaScript interviews than recursion.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;/blockquote&gt;

&lt;p&gt;If you just want to be impressive with recursion in JavaScript, here are some semi real-world (technical test type) examples.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;The short definition of a recursive solution to a problem (in computer science) is: donâ€™t use iteration. This usually means a function has to call itself with a smaller instance of the same problem until it hits a trivial case (usually defined in the problem).&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Hence, recursion is composed of a couple of steps:&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ol&gt;
&lt;li&gt;the base or terminating case, itâ€™s the situation we want to end up in â€œA recursive function definition has one or more &lt;em&gt;base cases&lt;/em&gt;, meaning input(s) for which the function produces a result &lt;a href=&#34;https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Trivial_(mathematics)&#34;&gt;trivially&lt;/a&gt; (without recurring)â€ - &lt;a href=&#34;https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Recursion_(computer_science)#Recursive_functions_and_algorithms&#34;&gt;Wikipedia, Recursion (computer science)&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;recursive case, where the program recurs (again &lt;a href=&#34;http://one or more recursive cases, meaning input(s) for which the program recurs (calls itself)&#34;&gt;Wikipedia, Recursion (computer science)&lt;/a&gt;)&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ol&gt;

